# 1️⃣ Arrays vs Vectors

---

# First Understand the Problem

Suppose you want to store student marks.

You write:

```cpp
int marks[5];
```

Looks fine.

But what if later you need:

```text
10 students
50 students
1000 students
```

Array size is fixed.

Problem ❌

---

# Array

## Simple Idea

Array = Fixed-size collection of same type data.

Example:

```cpp
int arr[5] = {10,20,30,40,50};
```

Memory:

```text
Index:  0   1   2   3   4
Value: 10  20  30  40  50
```

---

## Why Arrays Are Fast

Array elements are stored continuously.

```text
100 104 108 112 116
```

(assuming 4-byte integers)

Computer can jump directly to any index.

---

## Mental Model

```text
Array = Apartment with fixed rooms
```

If apartment has 5 rooms:

```text
Room 1
Room 2
Room 3
Room 4
Room 5
```

Cannot suddenly create Room 6.

---

# Problem with Arrays

Suppose:

```cpp
int arr[5];
```

Later:

```text
Need 6th element
```

Impossible.

---

# Vector

---

## Simple Idea

Vector = Dynamic Array

Example:

```cpp
vector<int> v;
```

Initially:

```text
Empty
```

Add values:

```cpp
v.push_back(10);
v.push_back(20);
v.push_back(30);
```

Now:

```text
10 20 30
```

---

# Why Vector Is Powerful

When full:

```text
10 20 30
```

Vector automatically creates larger memory.

Copies old elements.

Continues growing.

---

# Mental Model

```text
Vector = Expandable Apartment
```

Need more rooms?

Create bigger building automatically.

---

# Most Important Operations

---

## Add Element

```cpp
v.push_back(50);
```

---

## Remove Last Element

```cpp
v.pop_back();
```

---

## Size

```cpp
v.size();
```

---

## Access

```cpp
v[0]
v[1]
```

---

# Array vs Vector

| Feature            | Array     | Vector     |
| ------------------ | --------- | ---------- |
| Size               | Fixed     | Dynamic    |
| Memory             | Static    | Dynamic    |
| STL Support        | No        | Yes        |
| Easy Growth        | No        | Yes        |
| Used in Interviews | Sometimes | Very Often |

---

# Placement Tip 🔥

In coding rounds:

```text
Use vector unless fixed-size array is specifically needed.
```

Most professional C++ code uses vectors.

---

# How to Remember Forever

```text
Array = Fixed Box

Vector = Growing Box
```

---

# 2️⃣ Iterators (`begin()` and `end()`)

This is where many students get confused.

Let's make it simple.

---

# First Understand the Problem

Suppose:

```cpp
vector<int> v = {10,20,30,40};
```

How do we move through all elements?

We need a way to travel.

---

# Mental Model

Think:

```text
Iterator = Bookmark / Pointer for STL
```

It tells:

```text
Current position inside container
```

---

# Example

```cpp
vector<int> v = {10,20,30};

vector<int>::iterator it;
```

---

## What is `it`?

Think:

```text
it = traveler
```

moving through vector.

---

# begin()

```cpp
v.begin()
```

Returns iterator to first element.

Visualization:

```text
10 20 30
↑
it
```

---

# end()

```cpp
v.end()
```

Returns iterator AFTER last element.

Visualization:

```text
10 20 30
         ↑
      end()
```

Notice:

```text
Not on 30
After 30
```

Very important.

---

# Access Value

```cpp
auto it = v.begin();

cout << *it;
```

Output:

```text
10
```

---

# Why `*it`?

Remember pointers?

Iterator behaves similar to pointer.

```cpp
*it
```

means:

```text
Value at current position
```

---

# Move Forward

```cpp
it++;
```

Now:

```text
10 20 30
   ↑
```

---

# Example Traversal

```cpp
for(auto it = v.begin();
    it != v.end();
    it++)
{
    cout << *it << " ";
}
```

Output:

```text
10 20 30
```

---

# What Happens Internally?

Start:

```text
begin()
```

↓

Visit element

↓

Move next

↓

Repeat

↓

Reach `end()`

↓

Stop

---

# Modern Alternative

Most programmers now use:

```cpp
for(int x : v)
{
    cout << x;
}
```

Called:

```text
Range-Based Loop
```

But interviewers still ask iterators.

---

# Why Iterators Exist?

Because STL containers differ.

Examples:

```cpp
vector
list
set
map
```

Iterator gives one common way to traverse all.

---

# Mental Model

```text
Iterator = Universal Remote Control
```

Works with many STL containers.

---

# Connection to Pointers

Remember:

```cpp
int *p;
```

Pointer:

```text
Stores memory location
```

Iterator:

```text
Stores container position
```

Very similar idea.

---

# How to Remember Forever

```text
begin() → first element

end() → position after last element

iterator → traveler inside container
```

